Massive data resources are coming online in every conceivable area of human exploration, and particularly in heavily observation-based fields such as astronomy. Striking advances in both ground- and space-based instrumentation continuously increase the quality as well as the quantity of data available to astronomers. Enormous catalogs are being complied, and observations are made across the electromagnetic and gravitational spectrum providing multi-domain astrophysical measurements. These include high-resolution, but heterogeneous spectrography, imaging, and time series. Efficient statistical and computational methods play an instrumental role in scientists' endeavors to use these rich yet complex data to understand the physical environment and structure of astronomical sources, the processes governing their birth and death, and ultimately the structure and evolution of the universe. The required analytic tools for such scientific quests typically involve subtle tradeoffs between complexity and practicality and pose significant computational challenges.  The CHASC International Center for Astrostatistics has a long record of building such tools to address such specific challenges, and of further developing them into general methodologies for solving problems in many other fields. 

Specifically, this grant support has enabled the CHSAC team to 

Establish a new framework for formally characterizing unspecified extended structure in high-energy astrophysical images by computing upper bounds to the significance that a region of interest has a signal beyond that expected from a background; 
Develop new methods to identify solar regions with similar thermal activity by computing similarity measures in high-dimensional observational space and bypassing computationally intensive and mathematically unreliable inversion techniques; 
Construct classes of models for source disambiguation using multiple features such as differences in their positions as well as their spectral characteristics and temporal evolution; 
Prepare software that is freely available via platforms where they can be easily accessed by scientists interested in using the techniques, such as CRAN and github;
Develop principled methods that account for uncertainty in complex instrumental calibration and thereby provide an objective measure with which calibration scientists can improve the performance of space-based instrumentation;
Forecast the evolutionary paths of solar active regions using new tracking and classification techniques which will help to identify the characteristics of the solar corona when it is predisposed to flare; 
Determine the extent of a source present in the posterior distribution of a multi-scale LIRA analysis by computing the boundary of the source, thereby allowing scientifically interesting structures to be isolated and tracked.
Develop new Monte Carlo methods for more efficient computation.


These research accomplishments have the dual impact of more reliable statistical methods on astronomy and of the new statistical inference and computation methods on other fields. In addition to providing methods and free software, the CHASC team has also made extensive efforts to communicate to the astronomical community about the benefit of principled statistical methods, through workshops and sessions at conferences. 



